title: RC Aircraft Thrust Stand Version 2 - Hack of a Kitchen Scale for only $10

description.text: This is the second RC Thrust stand I have designed with the first being based on an Equal Arm Balance.  This one is more compact and does not require you to subtract out the weight of the components to find the absolute value of thrust produced.  It flies forward and pulls against the arms that drive into the weight (force / thrust) measuring sensors.  Not good at electronics to build something like this, no problem; buy a kitchen scale from amazon (Item # B00MN0NI90, "DecoBros Digital Food Scale") and hack it to harness the electronics.  I also purchased a 2 AAA battery holder from Radio Shack (shame they are all disappearing around here) instead of reusing the coin battery holder.  AAAs will last much longer.  Print the parts, Disassemble the scale and take care with the four sensor plates (follow the pictures).  After removing the metal plate on top of the scale (a couple of tabs and some double sided tape) I used a Dremel to cut through the plastic frame where shown (be careful of the wires).  I used a pair of flush cutters to remove the scale's feet from the sensor plates, don't use the dremel.  You don't want to change the metal plates by accidentally grinding them; this will change their accuracy to measure the thrust from the motor prop combo.  The plates have strain gauges on them under the sealer and are calibrated to measure the amount the metal bends as force presses on them.  For that matter, do not accidentally bend the tongue in the metal plates.  You can use screws to secure everything at the hinge points, but I successfully used 12 Gauge Aluminum Wire used to make arts and crafts.  It's soft and easy to flatten to a long hinge pin; and the holes are design for this.  Clamp or drill and screw the thrust stand to a permanent surface.  Make sure you leave room for prop to rotate.  Also try and not block the flow of air off the back of the prop.

comments.text: I'm making one of these (in the UK) at the moment and I bought a pair of kitchen scales from Lidl. I expected to have to redesign the item to fit the new parts, but actually, although the scales are more difficult to disassemble the strain gauges are exactly the same size as this design uses. The scales are  "Silvercrest" available in round or oblong version. They appear to be a Lidl own brand. £5.99 (UK May 2017). I bought the oblong ones. To disassemble them you have to prise the glass top away and carefully cut away the glue that holds the 4 strain gauges to the glass, and also the 2 control buttons. (I used a scalpel). I will need to redesign the front bit that holds the digital readout but all the mechanics of the item are just the same. Looking forward to trying it out.

comments.text: Bench tests complete. This measurement method proved to be as accurate as my other methods giving almost identical results within a couple counts difference here or there. This method also eliminates the need to subtract out the weight of components like is required with the equal arm balance method or other similar methods. This and it is really compact. Just be careful. In my comparison test I measured thrust of a Turnigy 2215J producing a maximum thrust of 705 grams on a 3S (I used a high current regulated supply to maintain voltage into the system throughout the test) using 147.5 watts and turning a 10x7 prop. This is a static thrust test so a slightly lower pitch prop may show better efficiency per gram of thrust (keep that in mind). Amazingly the power (W) to thrust (g) curve was basically linear; I expect the ends of the range to be rolled off. Print and enjoy:-)

description.text: This is my Vertical Spool Holder for my M3D Micro. The design of the base was made stronger since I didn't want any flimsy thing holding 2kg of filament on top of my printer. On this instance I've used high pressure PVC 1/2" inner diameter (21.4mm outer diameter). The rod has a cover so that it fits well into the bearings and two caps that allow easy slide in/out when changing filament. The bushings fits a filament spool with inner diameter of 1.25" and it houses a 28mm (outer diameter) bearing. The bearing's used here have a rubber/plastic cover, which you can see I removed on one of the pictures because it adds a bit of drag. I wanted it to be as smooth as possible so I trimmed about 0.5mm of the inner plastic cover. The clip helps stabilize the holder by completing the gab under the mount and fastening to it. title: Wall Mount for Vtech 6419 Cordless Phone

description.text:
My new cordless phone came with a horrible wall mount kit that only worked form the main base station and not for the satellite units.  After a few measurements and a couple of test prints, I had a aesthetic wall mount kit that performs great.  The satellite charger slips in the top and is held in by gravity.  The power cord feeds in through a hole in the bottom of the mount.  
I drew the design in FreeCAD.  I used the draft and fillet features to get a nice smooth shape that snuggly fits the provided base unit. Such operations would have been very difficult in openscad.

1) Print (I used abs at 0.20 mm 30% infill at 240C)
2) Mark and drill wall. Either into studs or use wall anchors
3) Screw up mount
4) Insert satellite charging station.
5) Connect power cord
6) Install phone.

author: maheshk22

title: Z-Axis Spacer Blocks, rc-lohas Stiffener Brackets

description.text: These are the spacer blocks i designed to work with the aluminum build plate stiffeners sold by rc-lohas on eBay. http://myworld.ebay.com/rc-lohas He redesigned his brackets and they now include holes for the screws that go though the back of the Z-Axis arms. If he doesn't have any for sale on eBay send him a message as he's probably out of stock! I helped him with the measurements on these and got the first couple pair made and installed a pair on my CTC, they will also fit Flashforge, Wanhao, and the Makerbot Replicator 1, i assume they will also fit the Rep 2 as the arms appear to be the same. Good quality and really do the job for keep the arms straight. Installation instructions... You will need 6 - 3mmx25mm screws, and 10 flat washers. The stiffeners come with four screws and allen screws for the adjustment. The washers i used are sold as rivet washers at most hardware stores, look for the pop rivets and rivet tools. These are about .75-.80mm thick and give just the right spacing. My local stores only carry 3mm screws in philips head so thats what i went with. Put the spacer on and then the aluminum stiffener, install the two side screws into the platform, just lightly tighten them so they can still move a bit to allow the bracket to slide front to back, then install the lower back screw only to act as a pivot point and install your two allen screws that come with the stiffeners. Tighten them so the allen screws are flush with the hole, this will force the upright portion back and straighten it and also line up the other two holes for the bracket. One my one side the hole was centered front to back but not top to bottom, slight variation in the castings, so i just cleaned it out with a 3mm drill bit. After installing the other two back screws tighten the two side screws and your done! To do this you really need to remove the build platform from the printer, but its not that hard it literally takes me like ten minutes to pull one of these out by unscrewing the Z-Axis motor mounting screws and removing the top Z-Axis bar plates, unscrew the motor from the platform and set it aside, pull the two Z-Axis bars up leaving their lower mounts in place, remove the platform, reinstall in the reverse order.

description.text: This is a very simple iPhone 4 / 4s mount for the Davinci XYZ 10. 3D Printer. The mount itself attaches to the top inside front of the printer where you will find a piece of angled metal coming out from the frame. I looked through the Da Vinci 1.0 to find a good mount point and this seem to be the best place. This allows for the 3D Printed Mount to be in place whilst allowing the door to remain closed. Right now the model is sufficient to hold the iPhone 4 in place but this could do with a modular upgrade to secure the iPhone better in place and to allow sideways movement for better framing. description.text:
Derived from Owen's fan duct design.  I liked the clip-on design, but  after a few high-speed prints, it started moving around.  I added "ears" that allows screws to be added to securely clamp the duct to the threaded rods as well as allow you to adjust the height.  
I added a rib to the interior of the duct to increase rigidity where it was a little weak due to the how it is printed.  I also added some "flats" to hold the hex nuts in position to make assembly easier.  I also removed a bit of material "here and there" to lighten it up a bit.  
Owen published his source Autodesk Inventor CAD file which is a great design - Thanks!  The modified Inventor and STEP files are included as well.  
Enjoy.

0.4 wall, 100% fill.  
I printed at 75 mm/s, 0.1 mm layer height.

The holes do not go through the lower layer to make it easier to print. You will have to drill them.
